    "# import libraries\n",
    "import numpy as np \n",
    "import pandas as pd \n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "588b3d28",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<font size = \"4\">\n",
    "\n",
    "**Q1** Random Assignment\n",
    "\n",
    "<font size = \"3\">\n",
    "\n",
    "- Read in the dataset named \"fifa23_players_basic.csv\", assigning it to a DataFrame object. Each row of the dataset corresponds to a professional soccer (football) player.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Use some method to randomly assign each player into two groups: \"A\" and \"B\". Each group should be assigned with equal probability (50% chance of being placed in either group). You can use any appropriate method to perform the random assignment.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Add a new column to the DataFrame with the name \"Group\", where each entry is either the string \"A\" or \"B\"."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "043055e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Solution 1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "76b45c2a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df_fifa = pd.read_csv(\"quiz_data/fifa23_players_basic.csv\")\n",
    "n = len(df_fifa)\n",
    "group_sample = np.random.choice([\"A\", \"B\"], size = n)\n",
    "df_fifa[\"Group\"] = group_sample"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "232b01b5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Solution 2"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "2abf2af8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df_fifa = pd.read_csv(\"quiz_data/fifa23_players_basic.csv\")\n",
    "n = len(df_fifa)\n",
    "\n",
    "rand_uniform = np.random.uniform(size = n)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_fifa[\"random_var\"] = rand_uniform\n",
    "\n",
    "def assign_group(num):\n",
    "    if num < 0.5:\n",
    "        return \"A\"\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        return \"B\"\n",
    "    \n",
    "df_fifa[\"Group\"] = df_fifa[\"random_var\"].apply(assign_group)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_fifa.drop(columns = \"random_var\", inplace = True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f23ac374",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<font size = \"4\">\n",
    "\n",
    "**Q2** Plotting two groups\n",
    "\n",
    "<font size = \"3\">\n",
    "\n",
    "- Continue to use the DataFrame you created in Q1\n",
    "\n",
    "- Use `.query` to extract all players in Group \"A\", assigning it to a new DataFrame called `groupA`\n",
    "\n",
    "- Use `.query` to extract all players in Group \"B\", assigning it to a new DataFrame called `groupB`\n",
    "\n",
    "- Use ``matplotlib.pyplot.subplots`` to create two side by side scatter plots (1 row, 2 columns)\n",
    "\n",
    "- In the left figure, plot the columns ``Age`` vs. ``Overall`` for the data in ``groupA`` (so the horizontal axis will correspond to \"Age\")\n",
    "- In the right figure, plot the columns ``Age`` vs. ``Overall`` for the data in ``groupB`` (so the horizontal axis will correspond to \"Age\")\n",
    "- Label the axes for both plots. Create a title for **both** plots, indicating whether Group A or Group B is shown.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Note**: If the assignment into groups was done randomly, then we expect that the scatter plots will be **very similar**\n",
    "\n",
    "**Hint**: ``matplotlib.pyplot.subplots`` was used in the Lecture 09 notebook on Random Variables. Solve the problem using two executions of `matplotlib.pyplot.scatter` first, then review how to use subplots."
   ]
  },
